g><\\/p><p>Lead By Michael Stadul<\\/p><p><strong><a href=\\\"mailto:marinac@touchedbycancer.org\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Click here<\\/a><\\/strong><strong> <\\/strong><strong>to email Susan Marinac, LISW-S, MT-BC, and let her know you are interested in Tai Chi. She will contact you to complete registration. Please include your name and phone number in the email.<\\/strong><\\/p>\",\"107\":\"\",\"176\":[\"158\"],\"200\":[\"150\"]}}','2015-03-05 20:43:35','2015-03-05 20:43:35','62330ce1-f547-4506-a97a-2a5c797a5345'),(135,113,4,4,'en_us',3,'','{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"4\",\"title\":\"One Step Closer\",\"slug\":\"one-step-closer\",\"postDate\":1425052200,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"174\":[\"82\"],\"177\":\"\",\"175\":[\"93\"],\"176\":[\"158\"],\"144\":[\"98\",\"100\",\"101\",\"102\"],\"87\":[\"35\"],\"67\":{\"114\":{\"type\":\"storyInfoBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"storyHeaderImage\":[\"97\"],\"storySubtitle\":\"Emily Survives Cancer and Shaves for a Cure\",\"storyText\":\"<p>After trying everything to cure her cancer, Emily was given three months to live. Then something amazing happened \\u2014 her cancer went away. Read Emily\'s survival story and learn why she shaves her head to raise money for childhood cancer research. <\\/p><p>I was given three months to live. That was 17 years ago. <\\/p><p>At the age of 11, I was diagnosed with late-stage osteosarcoma of the spine and ribs. As is typical with bone cancers, I had been having pain for a couple of months. But it wasn\'t until I injured my knee rollerskating and went completely paralyzed from the waist down that doctors found a grapefruit-sized tumor that had grown into four ribs, around my spine, and into my lungs. <\\/p><p>They found it with a simple X-ray. <\\/p><p><strong>My doctors gave me slim chances of either beating cancer or of regaining my ability walk.<\\/strong> When given a choice of protocol, I decided to go with the big guns: chemotherapy, heavy radiation, a massive 24-hour surgery, and a randomized experimental therapeutic trial of a drug that was created by a veterinarian for use in animals. <\\/p><p>In surgery, doctors took out four of my ribs, half of four vertebrae, the lower lobe of my left lung, put in two sets of titanium rods, fused my entire spine, did bone grafts, and implanted radiated seeds in a gortex mesh.<\\/p><p><strong>The surgery was a success, taking only 18 hours instead of the projected 24 hours. And I came out of it without becoming paralyzed once more. Life was going well.<\\/strong> I was still reacting positively to chemotherapy and radiation, and we knew I was receiving the experimental drug and not a placebo due to my response. I was gaining strength through physical therapy and had learned to walk again with assistance of a walker and crutches.<\\/p><p>And then it came. The call. The call where you end up in a windowless room with all your doctors and nurses and social workers. <strong>It\'s bad when you relapse. It\'s worse when you relapse while still on chemo. <\\/strong>I\'ll never forget that moment \\u2014 how sad my parents were, the shock on my brother\'s face. I still had options, but now the aim was to buy time, not a cure. <\\/p><p>Once again, I had a choice: more chemo or stop all treatments? I emphatically declined further treatments. I was at peace due to my personal faith and the faith I had in my doctors. I knew we had tried everything. I would take the three months they gave me and live. I would go to the top of Pike\'s Peak, see the Grand Canyon once more, celebrate my 21st birthday, go to prom, take one final vacation to Disney World, and spend my time with family and friends, watching as many sunrises and sunsets as I could along the way. Then a miracle happened. The metastasis in my lung went away during those three months, and I became cancer free. I choose to believe that a large part of my survival is due to the experimental treatment and having a team like the one I have. <\\/p><p><strong>My miracle is the biggest reason I am such a supporter of the St. Baldrick\'s-Stand Up to Cancer Pediatric Cancer Dream Team partnership. Kids need cures for cancer that don\'t ruin their bodies.<\\/strong> <\\/p><p>This miracle is why I\'ve shaved my head three times, and why I will shave again next year: <strong>With every head shaved, and every donation made, we are one step closer to better cancer treatments and finding cures for children like me and for all our friends. <\\/strong><\\/p>\",\"additionalImages\":\"\",\"accentText\":\"\\\"I still had options, but now the aim was to buy time, not for a cure.\\\"\",\"relevantLink\":\"http:\\/\\/\"}}},\"2\":\"\"}}','2015-03-06 17:33:28','2015-03-06 17:33:28','58f9b33d-7232-4468-bd0d-f27df60eaa12'),(136,35,4,4,'en_us',18,'','{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"4\",\"title\":\"Sample Story 1\",\"slug\":\"sample-story-1\",\"postDate\":1424217600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"174\":[\"82\"],\"177\":\"\",\"175\":\"\",\"176\":\"\",\"144\":[\"7\"],\"87\":[\"38\"],\"67\":{\"36\":{\"type\":\"storyInfoBlock\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"storyHeaderImage\":[\"134\"],\"storySubtitle\":\"The Gripping Tale of How I Tested Adding a Story\",\"storyText\":\"<p>Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, ius ex putent euripidis assentior, nec munere omnium accumsan eu, eam case aliquam nusquam ne. Eruditi corpora eu eum, ei mei malis scripserit. Porro quaestio efficiendi vis ad. Mel in audiam appellantur, ludus omittantur ut eam. No iusto consulatu mel, vel an wisi assum possim, accumsan invenire atomorum eum eu.<\\/p><p>Ne vidit vocibus referrentur ius, ne graeci electram vis. <em>Augue fuisset ut cum. <\\/em>Nibh meliore quo et. Ad nec sumo essent liberavisse, id eam modo scaevola. Has nostrud ullamcorper ea. Nec et purto lucilius. Ne nisl oportere eos, nec dicta phaedrum no.<\\/p><p><strong>Te duo scripta apeirian atomorum<\\/strong>, ad duo alii veniam tibique. Ne his oratio regione, ea duo ornatus sentent